Optimistic v Pessimistic Baseline

The two baselines differ in their capital costs and resulting ITC benefits. As well, the longer lifetime of the optimistic scenario likely drives higher overall revenues. As well, the optimistic baseline (baseline 1) participates more in energy arbitrage (DA ETS) than the pessimistic version; this is likely driven by the cap in daily cycles at 1 per day (as informed by sensitivity analysis below). Without the daily cycle limit, the optimistic scenario also provides more spinning reserves.

Sensitivity results on NPV - optimistic baseline

Increasing the length of the simulation to 120 hours does not have a large effect on the calculated NPV, meaning that we can use longer simulations (necessary with the newer version of storageVET). Reducing the daily cycle limit to 2 (from unlimited) does not have much effect, but reducing it to 1 cycle per day reduces the revenue significantly.

From most to least important sensitivities: FR prices (time_series_filename) cut by 90%, length of the project (increasing or decreasing by 5 years from a baselineof 15 years), discount rate (increasing to 10% or decreasing to 5% from 7%), RA prices (doubling), capital cost per kWh (increase by 25%), housekeeping power, cycle limit. Reducing the daily cycle limit to 2 (from unlimited) does not have much effect, but reducing it to 1 cycle per day reduces the revenue significantly. As well, installing a 4 hr battery instead of a 5 hr battery has a surprisingly small impact on lifetime revenue.

Sensitivity results on NPV - pessimistic baseline

Most to least important effects examined: 1. Length of project (double), 2. FR prices, 3. length of project (10 -> 15 yrs), 4. capital cost (decrease 500 > 400/kWh, or by 20%), 5. Increase RA prices (double), 6. Discount rate (increasing to 10% or decreasing to 5% from 7%), 7. Removing housekeeping power 8. Remove daily cycle limit 9. Increase length of simulation

The results are qualitatively similar to the sensitivities done on the optimistic baseline. Project lifetime and FR prices are very important to both; cycle limit and simulation length are relatively unimportant for each. The two show differet results in the importance of capital cost, which is more important in the pessimistic case than RA prices or discount rate. In the optimistic case, capital cost is less important than these other two factors. This difference can be likely attributed to the difference in project lifetime, since a larger lifetime effectively deweights the upfront cost.

Optimistic Baseline: Effect of sensitivities on costs

The only visible effect is on capital cost, though decreasing FR prices results in some costs associated with FR energy throughput. Interestingly, DA ETS (energy arbitrage) appears as negative in some scenarios, indicating that it was charging in the energy market to be dispatched later in another market.
